# Spekto — Stripe & Xero Orchestration: Process Flows and Schema Design

**Purpose:** This document describes, for each of the six payment scenarios in Spekto, exactly what happens at each step (Spekto DB → Stripe → Xero), and the database tables/columns needed to support it. This builds directly on `STRIPE_XERO_PLAN.md` — read that first for the overall principles (seamless charging, no Stripe Invoicing product, direct Edge Function → Xero sync rather than a third-party connector, refunds as new rows never edits). This document goes one level deeper into the actual schema and the less-common scenarios (partial refund, partial Scout payment, marketplace purchase) that the original plan only sketched.

---

## 0. New / Modified Tables Needed

These are additions on top of the existing schema — nothing here removes or renames anything already in place.

### `payments` (existing table — needs new columns)
This table already exists and is used by `handle_dispute_raised()`. It needs to become the **ledger of every money movement on the Client side** — one row per event, never edited after creation.

New columns needed:
- `payment_type` — text, CHECK constraint: `'Charge'`, `'Refund'`, `'PartialRefund'`, `'MarketplacePurchase'`
- `related_payment_id` — uuid, nullable, self-referencing FK to `payments.id` — set on a `Refund`/`PartialRefund` row to point back at the original `Charge` row it refunds. This is the mechanism that makes "never edit, always link" actually queryable.
- `stripe_payment_intent_id` — text (already noted as a planned column in `PROJECT_NOTES.md`)
- `stripe_refund_id` — text, nullable — populated only on refund rows
- `stripe_receipt_url` — text, nullable — store the **Payment Intent ID**, not a cached URL (per the expiry caution already documented); fetch a fresh receipt URL from Stripe at view time
- `xero_invoice_id` — text, nullable — the Xero-side record this payment was synced to
- `xero_sync_status` — text, CHECK: `'Pending'`, `'Synced'`, `'Failed'` — lets you detect and retry failed Xero syncs rather than silently losing them
- `amount` — numeric — always positive for `Charge`, always negative for `Refund`/`PartialRefund` (so summing all rows for an inspection gives the correct net amount directly)

### `payout_batch_items` (existing table — needs new columns)
Same ledger principle, applied to the Scout side.

New columns needed:
- `item_type` — text, CHECK: `'Payout'`, `'PartialPayout'`, `'PayoutAdjustment'`
- `related_item_id` — uuid, nullable, self-referencing FK — links an adjustment/reduction row back to the original payout item it modifies
- `stripe_transfer_id` — text, nullable
- `xero_bill_id` — text, nullable
- `xero_sync_status` — text, CHECK: `'Pending'`, `'Synced'`, `'Failed'`
- `amount` — numeric — the actual amount transferred for this specific row (may differ from the inspection's full Scout-payout amount if this is a `PartialPayout`)

### `marketplace_purchases` (existing table — needs new columns)
Currently has no Stripe/Xero linkage at all, since the purchase flow was stubbed. Needs the same treatment as `payments`.

New columns needed:
- `stripe_payment_intent_id` — text
- `stripe_receipt_url` — store Payment Intent ID, fetch receipt fresh (same pattern as above)
- `xero_invoice_id` — text, nullable
- `xero_sync_status` — text, CHECK: `'Pending'`, `'Synced'`, `'Failed'`
- `download_count` — integer, default 0 — needed to enforce the "max 3 downloads" rule already documented in pricing
- `access_expires_at` — timestamptz — needed to enforce the "48hr buyer access" rule already documented

### New table: `webhook_events`
A small but important addition not yet discussed. This is a log of every Stripe/Xero webhook received, used for two things: idempotency (never process the same webhook event twice, since Stripe/Xero can and do retry deliveries) and debugging (when something goes wrong, you need to see what was actually received, not just what your code did with it).

Columns: `id` (uuid), `source` (text — `'stripe'` or `'xero'`), `event_type` (text — e.g. `'payment_intent.succeeded'`), `event_id` (text — the provider's own unique event ID, with a UNIQUE constraint to enforce idempotency), `payload` (jsonb — the full raw event body), `processed` (boolean, default false), `processed_at` (timestamptz, nullable), `error` (text, nullable), `created_at` (timestamptz, default now()).

### New table: `fraud_flags`
Supports the mistake-vs-fraud classification described in Section 5/5a — full column definitions are in Section 5a, listed here for completeness of the schema overview. One row per detected signal, linked to `inspection_id`, `scout_id`, and optionally `capture_id`.

